# Markdown / Docs Rules

## Output discipline
- Show only the changed sections — use `<!-- ... -->` to elide unchanged ones if helpful.
- Don't reprint the table of contents unless it changed.
- Don't reformat existing prose while editing one section.

## Style matching
- Match existing heading depth and style (`#` vs `##` for top-level).
- Match existing list style (`-` vs `*`, ordered vs unordered).
- Match existing code-block fencing and language tags.

## When writing new docs
- Lead with the action, not the rationale.
- Use tables for comparisons, not paragraphs.
- Use code blocks for commands, not inline `like this` for multi-line content.
- Keep examples minimal — one is usually enough.

## What not to add
- Don't add "Introduction" sections for a single-page README that already starts with the title.
- Don't add "Conclusion" or "Summary" sections — the reader has the full doc.
- Don't add boilerplate sections (Prerequisites, Notes) unless content exists for them.
- Don't add badges, emojis, or "powered by" footers unless asked.

## Links & references
- Use relative links for in-repo references.
- Don't break existing anchor links by renaming headings — flag instead.

## Never
- Don't auto-generate a doc from code without being asked.
- Don't add a CONTRIBUTING / CHANGELOG / CODE_OF_CONDUCT section to a README.
- Don't translate docs — that's a separate task.
